[{"id":"VR725336","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">An object of mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"M\"><math alttext=\"M\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>M</mi></math></span></span> is free to move along a curved track with negligible friction. The shape of the track results in the following equation that expresses Newton’s second law for the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"x\"><math alttext=\"x\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>x</mi></math></span></span>-coordinate of the object’s motion: <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"M times the second derivative of x with respect to t squared equals beta times, open parenthesis, x minus x sub 0, close parenthesis\"><math alttext=\"M times the second derivative of x with respect to t squared equals beta times, open parenthesis, x minus x sub 0, close parenthesis\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>M</mi><mfrac><mrow><msup><mi>d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi><msup><mi>t</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>β</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>−</mo><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>)</mo></mrow></math></span></span>, where <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t\"><math alttext=\"t\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>t</mi></math></span></span> is time, <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"beta\"><math alttext=\"beta\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>β</mi></math></span></span> is a positive constant with appropriate units, and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"x sub 0\"><math alttext=\"x sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span></span> is a position where the object’s acceleration is zero in the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"x\"><math alttext=\"x\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>x</mi></math></span></span>-direction. If the object is released from rest on the track at an initial position other than <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"x sub 0\"><math alttext=\"x sub 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>x</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></span></span>, will its <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"x\"><math alttext=\"x\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>x</mi></math></span></span>-coordinate exhibit simple harmonic motion? What reasoning or evidence supports the claim?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR725336_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Yes. The net force is a linear function of position.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Yes. There is an equilibrium position where the net force is zero.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">No. The net force is not zero at <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"x equals 0\"><math alttext=\"x equals 0\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></span></span>.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">No. The net force is not in the opposite direction from the object’s displacement from equilibrium.</p>"],"answer":3}]